results.notes:
Growing scattered in mossy, acidic soil along a cold, fast moving and rocky stream. In an oak-pine forest with a dense ericaceous understory. Near Quercus montana, Pinus strobus, Oxydendron arboreum, Kalmia latifolia, Rhododendron sp., Leucothoe fontanesiana, and Vaccinium sp. Quercus alba, Quercus rubra and Carya spp. also present in the general area. Caps inately fibrillose and hygrophanous; up to 7.3 mm wide and 2.6 mm tall. Gills adnexed to sinuate with 1 tier of lamellulae. Stems pruinose with white basal mycelium; up to 15.7 mm long and 1.1 mm wide. Surfaces not bruising. Odor abd taste not distinctive. Spores dull brown in mass. Pleurocystidia similar to cheilocustidia. Cheilocystidia metuloid and apically incrusted. Basidia 4-sterigmate. Spores nodulose. results.notes:
Found nestled between and emerging from a piece of rotting wood under small 1-2 in. rocks in a small cluster, in the front yard behind a shed. Partially concealed by oak leaves. Growing 4-6 feet from oaks and other hardwood trees. Mushroom appeared short on the surface but the entire fruiting body, once excavated was much longer than what was above ground. Caps are mostly red and orange with a slight nipple. Very ends of are cream or beige colored. Has a distinctive smell. No rings found/noticed. Gills are widely-spaced w/ adnexed hymenium. Stems have variating splotches of dark orange and and beige and are serpentine in form. Does not have enough similarities to poisonous Jack-O-Lantern species or a False Chanterelle. More closely resembles the deadly Galerina, but I am no expert. Falls into LBMs. In the process of taking sporeprints. Noticed purple bruising.

Update 01/04/22: Added sporeprint to observation. It appears purplish brown, almost like a chocolate color. I would not call it rusty. I am starting to doubt that it is a Galerina. Is it some psychoactive species? The literature on Psylocybes and other “magic” mushrooms is lacking in our state, though they do grow here. Seems exactly like a Psilocybe subaeruginosa, except those apparently don’t grow here at all.
